.docname {Run the Application}
.include {docs}

CrowdVision can be run in two distinct modes: **Docker Compose** for everyday local development, and **Kubernetes** for production-like environments. Both modes are managed via `just` recipes from the monorepo root.

---

## 🐳 Docker Compose Mode

### Development (Hot-Reloading)

For active development with live code reloading, use:

```bash
just dev
```

**What happens:**
1. `just env` runs first to verify your `.env` and generate any missing keys.
2. A runtime compose file is generated that includes all service compose files.
3. Docker Compose launches with `--watch` — saving a file triggers an instant hot-reload inside the running container.
4. All services start: Caddy proxy, Redis, all MongoDB instances, all backend microservices, and the Vue client.

### Excluding Services

The `agent-service` is the heaviest service (Python + model loading). Skip it when you are not working on AI features:

```bash
# Exclude by substring of folder name:
just dev exclude="agent"

# Exclude multiple services (space-separated):
just dev exclude="agent simulator"

# Exclude the client (useful when running it separately with Vite):
just dev exclude="client"
```

.box type:{note}
    Exclusion matches by **folder name substring**. `"agent"` will skip `server/agent-service`, `agent-db`, and any folder containing "agent". Use a more specific substring if needed.

### Accessing the Application (Docker mode)

.var {headers}
   - Interface
   - URL
   - Description

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - Vue Frontend
      - `http://localhost:8080`
      - The main CrowdVision user interface.
    - - API Gateway
      - `http://localhost:80`
      - Caddy proxy — routes to all microservices.
    - - Agent API Docs
      - `http://localhost/agent/docs`
      - FastAPI/OpenAPI reference for `/ask`, `/ingest`, and `/health`.
    - - Auth DB GUI
      - `http://localhost/auth-db-gui/`
      - Mongo Express for the auth database. Dev mode only.
    - - Twin DB GUI
      - `http://localhost/twin-db-gui/`
      - Mongo Express for the twin database. Dev mode only.
    - - Grafana
      - `http://localhost/grafana/`
      - Metrics dashboards. Dev mode only.
    - - Prometheus
      - `http://localhost/prometheus/`
      - Raw metrics scraper. Dev mode only.
    - - Langfuse
      - `http://localhost:3030`
      - AI-agent traces, tool calls, tokens, cost, and latency. Docker mode only.

### Langfuse Login

Langfuse is the trace UI for `agent-service`. Open `http://localhost:3030` directly, or
open `http://localhost/langfuse` to be redirected there.

The Docker Compose development defaults are:

.var {headers}
   - Field
   - Default

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - Email
      - `admin@crowd-vision.local`
    - - Password
      - `langfuse-admin`

Override the defaults in the root `.env` before starting Langfuse for the first time:

```bash
LANGFUSE_INIT_USER_EMAIL=your-email@example.com
LANGFUSE_INIT_USER_PASSWORD=use-a-strong-password
```

.box type:{warning}
    The `LANGFUSE_INIT_USER_*` values provision the initial account when the Langfuse
    database is first created. Changing them later does not update an existing user's
    login. For any shared or externally reachable deployment, replace the development
    password before first startup.

.box type:{note}
    Langfuse is currently included in the Docker Compose stack only. The repository's
    Kubernetes manifests do not deploy or expose Langfuse.

### Agent Operations

```bash
just logs agent-service       # follow application logs and console traces
just agent-ingest             # ingest developer + user documentation
just test-agent               # Moon-managed agent pytest task
just test-agent-integration   # Testcontainers/Postgres integration suite
just eval                     # evaluate the configured answer model
just eval models="a,b"        # compare answer models end to end
```

The automatic `agent-ingester` runs once during Docker Compose startup after
`agent-service` becomes healthy. Kubernetes does not deploy this ingester, so documents
must be ingested manually after deployment.

For provider verification, model evaluation, API examples, permissions, and current
limitations, see the [Agent Service](../services/agent.qd) guide.

`just eval` makes real provider requests and requires a running, already-ingested stack.
Local runs mint a fresh JWT for every request from the repository `.env`. `just eval`
reports scored `FAIL`, `XFAIL`, and `XPASS` results without failing the recipe; setup and
preflight errors still fail. Direct runner invocations exit non-zero on unexpected
failures and can use `--strict` to also fail on stale `XPASS` markers.

### Production / Detached Mode

```bash
just start
```

Runs the stack using the base compose configuration in detached mode (`-d`). No hot-reloading, no database GUIs. Same `exclude=` syntax works here too.

### Stopping & Resetting

```bash
# Graceful shutdown — stops all containers and removes orphans:
just down

# Follow logs for all services:
just logs

# Follow logs for one service:
just logs auth-service

# Wipe all databases (destructive — you will need to re-provision):
just db-clear

# Wipe only the sensor database:
just db-clear-sensor
```

.box type:{warning}
    `just db-clear` permanently deletes all persistent Docker volumes. You will need to run `node scripts/ops/provision.js` again after a clear to recreate the admin account.

---

## 🌱 Bootstrapping (First-Time Provisioning)

With empty databases you cannot log in. Use the provisioning script to seed the initial Global Admin account and default Domain:

```bash
node scripts/ops/provision.js
```

Run this once after your services are healthy. The script prompts you for the admin email, password, and domain name, then calls the running auth-service to register them.

---

## ☸️ Kubernetes Mode

See the [Kubernetes Configuration](kubernetes.qd) page for the full reference. Quick summary:

### First Time: Creating the Cluster

```bash
k3d cluster create crowdvision \
  --servers 1 \
  --agents 3 \
  --api-port 127.0.0.1:6550 \
  -p "80:80@loadbalancer" \
  -p "443:443@loadbalancer" \
  --k3s-arg "--disable=traefik@server:*"
```

### Deploying (Production images from GHCR)

```bash
# First-time full setup (ingress controller → namespace → secrets → manifests):
just k8s-setup

# Subsequent deploys — re-apply manifests:
just k8s-apply
```

### Deploying with Locally Built Images (k3d dev)

```bash
just k8s-build      # build all images locally
just k8s-load       # import into k3d — no GHCR needed
just k8s-apply      # apply manifests
```

### Updating a Single Service

```bash
# After code changes — rebuild the image, then rolling restart:
docker build -t ghcr.io/nickghignatti/crowdvision-auth:latest ./server/auth-service
just k8s-load
just k8s-restart auth-service

# Watch the rollout:
just k8s-rollout auth-service
```

### Managing Cluster Lifecycle

```bash
# Pause the cluster (preserves all pods, volumes, and secrets):
just k8s-stop

# Resume from exactly where you left off (~30 seconds):
just k8s-start

# Verify everything came back up:
just k8s-status

# Destroy the cluster completely (data is permanently lost):
just k8s-delete
```

.box type:{note}
    Use `just k8s-stop` at the end of your working day. All pod state and persistent volume data survives the stop/start cycle — your databases are intact.

### Verifying Cluster Health

```bash
# All pods should show 1/1 Running:
just k8s-status

# Check persistent volumes are Bound:
kubectl get pvc -n crowdvision

# Check Ingress has an ADDRESS:
kubectl get ingress -n crowdvision

# Tail logs for a service:
just k8s-logs auth-service

# Describe a pod for detailed events (useful for debugging):
kubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n crowdvision
```

---

## 🧪 Testing

```bash
# Run all unit tests across all services (moon caches results — unchanged services are instant):
just test

# Run only tests for services touched by your current branch:
just test-affected

# Per-service unit tests:
just test-auth
just test-twin
just test-sensor
just test-notification
just test-socket
just test-client
just test-agent

# Full backend integration tests (spins up a composed stack, then tears it down):
just test-integration
```

.box type:{note}
    `just test` and `just lint` both delegate to **moon**, which caches task results by input hash. If nothing in a service has changed since the last run, the cached result is replayed in milliseconds. Use `just test-affected` / `just lint-affected` on a feature branch to only process the services your changes actually touch.

---

## 🔒 Auditing & Dependency Checks

Two recipes run a security audit and a lockfile-sync check across every project. Both delegate to **moon** (`moon run :audit` / `:deps`), so they are cached and accept `--affected` to scope to the projects changed on your branch. See [The Toolchain: mise & moon](toolchain.qd) for how these tasks are defined.

```bash
# Security audit — npm audit (--audit-level=high --omit=dev) + uv audit + cargo audit:
just audit

# Lockfile-sync check — npm ci + uv sync --locked + cargo check:
just deps-check

# Scope either to only the projects changed on your branch:
mise exec -- moon run :audit --affected
```

.box type:{note}
    `just deps-check` is the fastest way to catch a lockfile drift before pushing (the classic `npm ci can only install packages when your package.json and package-lock.json are in sync`). If it fails, regenerate the offending lockfile with `just clean-install` (see [Setting Up the Environment](setting-up.qd) → *Lockfiles & Cross-Platform Regeneration*). The Rust `cargo audit` leg is marked **allow-failure**: if `cargo-audit` isn't installed it is reported but does not fail the run (`cargo install cargo-audit` to enable it).

---

## 📋 Full Just Reference — Docker Compose

.var {headers}
   - Recipe
   - What it does

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - `just dev [exclude="..."]`
      - Full stack with hot-reloading. Optionally exclude services.
    - - `just start [exclude="..."]`
      - Full stack in detached/production mode.
    - - `just down`
      - Graceful shutdown, removes orphan containers.
    - - `just logs [service]`
      - Follow logs. Omit service to tail all.
    - - `just db-clear`
      - Drop all databases (destructive).
    - - `just db-clear-sensor`
      - Drop only the sensor database.
    - - `just test`
      - Run all unit tests (moon-cached; unchanged services are instant).
    - - `just test-affected`
      - Run unit tests only for services changed on the current branch.
    - - `just test-<service>`
      - Run unit tests for one service.
    - - `just test-integration`
      - Run backend integration tests.
    - - `just lint`
      - Lint every service (moon-cached).
    - - `just lint-affected`
      - Lint only services changed on the current branch.
    - - `just lint-fix`
      - Auto-fix linting issues across every service.
    - - `just agent-ingest`
      - Re-ingest documentation into the AI agent knowledge base.
    - - `just audit`
      - Security audit across all projects via `moon run :audit` (npm + uv + cargo).
    - - `just deps-check`
      - Lockfile-sync check across all projects via `moon run :deps` (npm ci + uv sync --locked + cargo check).
    - - `just clean-install`
      - Wipe all node_modules + lockfiles and regenerate them for Linux, then reinstall.
    - - `just docs`
      - Compile both Quarkdown guides to `landing-page/{user,dev}` (mirrors CI).
    - - `just docs-preview [dir=...]`
      - Quarkdown live-reloading server for one guide while editing.
    - - `just docs-serve`
      - Build both guides, then live-serve the whole `landing-page/` site at `:8080`.

---

## 🔍 Debugging Tips

### A service is responding with 502 Bad Gateway

The Caddy proxy forwards to the service container but nothing is listening. Most common causes:

**1. The `dev` script in `package.json` points to a non-existent file.**
Every Node.js/TypeScript service must reference `src/index.ts` via `ts-node/esm`, not a compiled `.js` file. Check the service's `package.json`:

```bash
# Correct pattern (all TypeScript services):
"dev": "nodemon --watch src --exec node --no-warnings=ExperimentalWarning --loader ts-node/esm src/index.ts"
```

If it says `src/index.js` and that file does not exist, nodemon exits silently and the service never starts — manifesting as 502.

**2. Environment variable is empty or wrong.**
Open the service logs: `just logs <service-name>`. Look for connection errors to MongoDB or Redis at startup.

**3. Missing `.env` variable.**
Run `just env` to fill any gaps. The script skips variables already present, so it is safe to re-run.

---

### `just dev exclude="..."` is not excluding the service

Exclusion works by matching the **folder name substring**. Examples:

```bash
just dev exclude="agent"          # skips server/agent-service, agent-db, agent-ingester
just dev exclude="agent simulator"  # also skips aq-simulator, sensor-simulator
```

If exclusion suddenly stops working after editing the Justfile: verify that `dev` still takes only ONE parameter (`exclude=""`). Adding a second parameter before `exclude` in the recipe definition breaks named-argument resolution in `just`.

---

### Windows: `kubectl` fails to connect after `just k8s-start`

After a cluster restart the kubeconfig may point to a stale port. Fix it:

```bash
# Find the actual port the k3d load balancer is using:
docker ps --filter name=k3d-crowdvision-serverlb
# Look for the port mapped to 6443 in the PORTS column, e.g. 0.0.0.0:32774->6443/tcp

# Update the kubeconfig to use the correct port:
kubectl config set-cluster k3d-crowdvision --server=https://127.0.0.1:<PORT>
```

---

### `just k8s-secrets` fails: "namespaces not found"

Secrets are scoped to the `crowdvision` namespace — it must exist first. Create it manually:

```bash
kubectl apply -f k8s/namespace.yml
just k8s-secrets
```

Or use `just k8s-setup` which handles the ordering automatically.

---

### k3d image pull fails (ImagePullBackOff)

If pods are stuck in `ImagePullBackOff`, Kubernetes is trying to pull from GHCR instead of using the locally loaded image.

```bash
# Load images from your local Docker daemon into k3d:
just k8s-build
just k8s-load
```

Also check that the deployment manifest sets `imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent`, not `Always` — `Always` forces a remote pull even when the image exists locally.

---

### agent-service fails to start (database migration error)

The agent-service reads its Postgres connection string from `POSTGRES_URL` (not `DATABASE_URL`). Verify the secret was created correctly:

```bash
kubectl get secret agent-service-secret -n crowdvision \
  -o jsonpath='{.data.POSTGRES_URL}' | base64 -d
```

If it is empty or missing, check your `.env` for `POSTGRES_URL` and re-run `just k8s-secrets`.

---

### agent-service provider requests return `401`, `402`, or model errors

The agent uses one OpenAI-compatible endpoint for chat and embeddings. Verify that the
provider key matches the endpoint:

```bash
cd server/agent-service
OPENROUTER_API_KEY=<your-key> uv run python scripts/verify_provider.py
```

For the default OpenRouter endpoint, configure `OPENROUTER_API_KEY`. A `402` commonly means
the OpenRouter account lacks credit for the selected model; lower `MAX_OUTPUT_TOKENS` or use
a cheaper allowed model.

---

### agent answers documentation questions with no useful sources

Re-ingest the documentation and inspect the agent logs:

```bash
just agent-ingest
just logs agent-service
```

The Docker ingester loads `documentation/user` and `documentation/developer`. Kubernetes
does not run it automatically. Retrieval also filters documents against JWT roles/domains;
empty document permissions are visible to every authenticated caller.

---

### nginx Ingress rejects `configuration-snippet` annotation

Newer versions of the nginx Ingress Controller disable snippet annotations by default. If you see:

```text
annotation nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/configuration-snippet is not allowed
```

Re-install the ingress controller with snippets enabled:

```bash
helm upgrade ingress-nginx ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx \
  --namespace ingress-nginx \
  --set controller.allowSnippetAnnotations=true
```
